comment.narrative:
7. Target achieved. Environmental information on land use and biodiversity (snow leopard and its prey species) in Western Tian Shan and Gissar snow leopard landscapes collected and mapped. The information/data will be integrated to the BCIMS (Biodiversity Conservation Information Management System) to be installed in 2019. 

8. Snow leopard monitoring system is developed and is currently being reviewed by respective state nature conservation agencies. Two field expeditions for recognizing study sites and data collection on Snow leopard prey species (marmots) In Gissar and Pskem sub-regions were conducted. 
9. Recommendations on zoning of the project territories, namely for four protected areas, Ugam Chatkal Nature Park, Chatkal State Biosphere Reserve, Ugam Chatkal State Biosphere Reserve, and Gissar Reserve were developed. Zonation plans for these protected areas are prepared and will be further discussed with respective state agencies in 2019. 
10 and 11. Preparatory work has been conducted for introduction of smart patrol system in two pilot protected areas, Chatkal State Biosphere Reserve and Gissar State Reserve. Four project protected area inspectors together with Goscomecology Bioinspection state inspectors, in total of 6 persons, participated in smart patrol training in Bishkek and received certificates. Moreover, a study tour was organized in Bhutan, where smart patrol system is being implemented successfully, in close cooperation with WWF Bhutan and Bhutan Royal Ministry of Agriculture and Forestry with representatives from project pilot protected areas (four) and from their state administrations (Goscomecology, Goscomles, and JSC Uzbekistan temir yullari (Uzbekistan railways). Currently, the project is in process of concluding a contract with an international nature conservation agency for introduction of a smart patrol system in Uzbekistan.
14. A set of documents have been prepared as a contribution to the successful implementation of cooperative form among pasture users for the creation of prerequisites for the associated pasture use on the project pilot territories. Potential pasture users (80 pasture users) are trained on the basics of planning and various economic and mathematical methods for assessing the state of pastures. Agrotechnical measures are implemented to create local sites (4 ha) of primary seed production, with the help of which local pasture users will be provided with own seeds of forage plants for the enrichment of pastures used in the long term. Field researches were carried out and primary field materials for the detailed analysis of local conditions in the following directions is collected:
(a) geobotanical status of pasture areas for two seasons (summer and autumn);
b) structure and types of pastures in the project pilot areas;
C) structure and types of livestock in the project pilot areas;
d) socio-economic aspects of the livelihood of local population in the project areas.
Representatives of national and regional agencies were familiarized with the positive experience of associated pasture use management on international scale through participation in the study tour to Kyrgyzstan. Awareness-raising round tables and seminars on the establishment of cooperatives among pasture users in mountain and foothill areas at the local and national levels were held. Key possible national legislative and regulatory documents based on a critical analysis of the current state of implementing cooperative forms in pasture use management were systemized to improve the use of pastures on the ground. With the support of the project, a pilot pasture cooperative was created among local pasture users in one of the pilot areas (Akhangaran district of Tashkent region), Western Tian Shan snow leopard landscape.

16. The main directions and readiness of the population for alternative types of economic activities were initially identified through training workshops on increasing the potential of the local population in preparation of business plans for grant funding under the project and other financial sources. 101 representatives (41 of them women) of the local population and economic entities took part in the workshops. Eligibility criteria have been prepared, including the selection procedure and the composition of selection committee to provide grant funding for field and alternative activities to improve livestock management and the creation of alternative types of economic activities.
As a result of seminars, more than 30 applications were prepared for funding. The selection Committee for micro-grants selected 9 potential applications and obtained 6 funding permits from the local committees. The remaining 3 applications are prepared for approval by local committees and local authorities. Agreements were drawn up and documents were prepared for 6 approved applications to start procurement of equipment and necessary materials. 3 applications for micro-grant financing for construction, reconstruction and repair of facilities for stables, 2 applications for planting and/or purchase of feed for livestock, resulting in reduced load on natural pastures and reduction of grazing, were prepared from the side of local residents living in the pilot areas. Agreements were signed with two local representatives for micro-grants financing for the management of alternative activities to livestock, such as beekeeping and the manufacture of local clothing. To date, purchases have been made and equipment has been delivered to the beneficiaries. An agreement was signed with the local community on the creation of a small production line processing of fruit and berry products, in order to demonstrate and involve local farmers in horticulture, an alternative to livestock grazing. 
17. Tree nurseries have been established in both project areas (2 ha in Akhangaran district of Tashkent region and 2 ha in Shakhrisabz district of Kashkadarya region) to provide the population with saplings for the expansion of tree plots in the following years of the project implementation and after its completion. For the current expansion of forest areas, the local population is provided with various types of tree plants and auxiliary materials for the expansion of areas with trees in the communities (per 3 communities in Western Tian Shan and Gissar snow leopard landscapes). The capacity of residents in the project pilot sites to expand and care for forest areas, as well as storage and sale of fruits was increased through practical field training workshops in both project pilot areas. The capacity of local communities of the pilot areas is increased through a series of training workshops on the basics of using alternative energy sources (3 communities in Western Tian Shan and 2 communities in Gissar snow leopard landscapes). A field analysis was carried out on identification of types of alternative energy sources for communities. The preconditions for the establishment of a biological laboratory in the Ugam-Chatkal National Park created to prevent natural forest areas loss from diseases and pests. The study performed, and recommendations prepared for improving the management of forestry enterprises in the field. A plan prepared to improve the activities of forestry enterprises in the framework of increasing the sustainability of the use of natural forest areas. 
18. The capacity of the local population and local enterprises has been improved through trainings on preparing business plans for grant funding applications, during which candidates for the creation of gardens, wood areas and alternative energy sources have been selected. More than 40 families expressed their interest to participate directly in these activities of the project. The types of trees necessary for the distribution in the project pilot areas among the population for the primary provision of private plots with saplings in order to increase their own timber and fuel reserves have been agreed with the local forestry enterprise and communities. Grant agreement has been concluded with three communities for establishment of an orchard for fruit production. 
The project began a survey of the two project pilot areas in terms of possibilities and procedures to implement alternative energy sources. A contract was signed with a research production company to conduct a survey, familiarize the population with basic knowledge on the use of alternative energy sources, and to prepare recommendations on the structure and distribution of alternative energy sources on the ground.
19. Final draft of the programme and action plan completed, which will be submitted to Goscomecology for adoption in 2019.
21. Uzbekistan participated in a number of international events related to snow leopard and mountain ecosystems conservation in 2018:
- international conference on mid-term review of Central Asian Mammals Initiative of the CMS, 16-19 April 2018 in Bonn, Germany;
- CITES workshop for Central Asian countries on improving national frameworks for effective implementation of CITES convention, 22-25 May 2018 in Bishkek, Kyrgyz Republic;
- GSLEP Steering Committee meeting, 14-15 June 2018 in Bishkek, Kyrgyz Republic;
- International Euroasia conference on biodiversity conservation, 6-10 August 2018 in Bishkek, Kyrgyz Republic;
- International conference on snow leopard conservation, 3-7 September 2018 in Shenzhen, China;
- 70th session of COP of CITES, 1-5 October 2018 in Sochi, Russian Federation. 
22. Multilateral meetings were held with regional partner organizations during a working visit of the project to the Kyrgyz Republic for discussion of possibilities of transboundary cooperation during May17-21, 2018; consultative workshop on transboundary cooperation for snow leopard conservation between Uzbekistan, Tajikistan, Kyrgyz Republic, Kazakhstan and GSLEP was organized and held in Tashkent during July 16-20, 2018; drafts of MoU and Action Plan on transboundary snow leopard research and conservation prepared and discussed during consultative workshop. The final drafts of MOU and action plan on transboundary cooperation have been prepared.
